  "hypotheses": [
    {
      "id": "h1",
      "statement": "Spearman r(delta-r of target node, mean PRISM LFC for drugs targeting that node) < -0.40 across the 7 pre-specified node-drug class pairs (MDM2, mTOR, MYC, EGFR, AKT1, PI3K, MEK1). Cell lines: all lung_NSC lines in PRISM with valid depmap_id. Drug lists: exactly as specified in drug_node_mapping. delta-r values: from NSCLC perturbation loop on examples/nsclc_egfr_signaling.json (layers: physical_interaction vs coexpression_cancer), run 2026-06-06, baseline r=0.7145. Structural prediction: higher delta-r (ODS Damper) -> stronger cancer cell killing (more negative LFC) -> Spearman r is negative. n=7 pairs; at n=7 the minimum r for p<0.05 two-tailed is ~0.755. The -0.40 threshold is an effect size threshold, not a significance threshold. Known limitation: KRAS (the largest ODS Damper, delta-r=+0.061) has no specific KRAS inhibitor in PRISM 20Q2; KRAS is excluded from the analysis. ERK1 (largest anchor, delta-r=-0.135) has only 1 PRISM entry (CID-5458317) and is also excluded."
    },
    {
      "id": "h2",
      "statement": "ODS Damper drug classes (MDM2, mTOR, MYC) will show more negative mean PRISM LFC (averaged across all lung_NSC lines) than Structural Anchor drug classes (EGFR, AKT1, PI3K, MEK1). Measured as: mean(LFC for damper drugs) < mean(LFC for anchor drugs). This is a categorical test of ODS drug prediction without assuming linearity."
    }
  ],
